First I changed the unzip method to use bytes instead, but that still returned the same result. I paid very close attention this time and noticed that the unzip method was returning only 526 bytes of the 1024 bytes I was expecting (16 x 16 x 4). This seemed to indicate improper handling of the unzipped data, so I googled around to find the proper way to unzip gzipped byte data.

Two quick source code changes later and it&#39;s working fine now!

First, have the method properly use only byte arrays, and an actual buffer:


```
    public static byte[] unzip(String b64) {
        ByteArrayOutputStream os = new ByteArrayOutputStream();
        try {
            byte[] bytes = Base64.getDecoder().decode(b64);
            GZIPInputStream gis = new GZIPInputStream(new ByteArrayInputStream(bytes));
            byte[] buffer = new byte[1024];
            int len;
            while ((len = gis.read(buffer)) != -1){
                os.write(buffer, 0, len);
            }
            os.close();
            gis.close();
            return os.toByteArray();
        } catch (Exception e) {
            return new byte[1];
        }
    }
```
